                        <td>6.99%</td>
                      </tr>
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  Married filing jointly and head‑of‑household filers use the
                  same rates but with higher income thresholds. The calculator
                  automatically applies the appropriate thresholds based on the
                  filing status you select.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step‑by‑step calculation</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose your filing status.</strong> This determines
                  which set of Connecticut brackets apply.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your Connecticut taxable income.</strong> This
                  is your income after all CT deductions and exemptions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply the progressive brackets.</strong> The
                  calculator:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Splits your income across each bracket range.</li>
                    <li>
                      Multiplies the amount in each bracket by that bracket’s
                      rate.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Sums the results to get your
                      <strong>gross CT tax</strong>.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Subtract CT credits.</strong> Any credits you enter
                  (e.g., property tax credit) are subtracted dollar‑for‑dollar
                  from your CT tax, but not below zero.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare to withholding.</strong> If you enter
                  Connecticut tax already withheld, the calculator estimates
                  whether you may owe additional tax or receive a refund.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <p>The core of the calculation is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>CT tax before credits</strong> = sum over all brackets
                  of
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  \( \text{Tax}_i = \max\big(0, \min(\text{Income},
                  \text{Upper}_i) - \text{Lower}_i\big) \times \text{Rate}_i \)
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>CT tax after credits</strong> = max(0, CT tax before
                  credits − CT credits)
                </p>
                <p class="mb-1">
                  <strong>Effective CT tax rate</strong> = (CT tax after credits
                  ÷ CT taxable income)
                </p>
                <p class="mb-0">
                  <strong>Top marginal CT rate</strong> = rate of the highest
                  bracket that contains at least $1 of your income
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Resident vs. nonresident and part‑year resident</h2>
              <p>
                Connecticut has different forms for
                <strong>full‑year residents (CT‑1040)</strong> and
                <strong>nonresidents/part‑year residents (CT‑1040NR/PY)</strong
                >.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Residents</strong> are generally taxed on all income,
                  with credits for tax paid to other states.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Nonresidents</strong> are taxed only on
                  <strong>Connecticut‑source income</strong> (e.g., wages earned
                  in CT, CT rental property).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Part‑year residents</strong> file as residents for the
                  months they lived in CT and nonresidents for the rest.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on the
                <strong>tax on Connecticut‑taxable income</strong>. For
                nonresidents and part‑year residents, you can enter just your
                CT‑source taxable income to approximate the CT tax on that
                portion, but the official forms also include allocation ratios
                and credits that are not modeled here.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator uses a simplified version of the Connecticut
                  bracket thresholds and does not model every special deduction
                  or phase‑out.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not compute:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Credits for taxes paid to other states</li>
                    <li>
                      Detailed treatment of Social Security, pensions, or
                      municipal bond interest
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Household‑specific credits that require multi‑step
                      worksheets
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are estimates for planning and education only and are
                  <strong>not a substitute for professional tax advice</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Connecticut income tax</h2>

              <h3>Does Connecticut have local income taxes?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Unlike some states, Connecticut does
                <strong>not</strong> have city or county income taxes. The
                calculator only needs to consider the statewide CT income tax.
              </p>

              <h3>
                How do Connecticut tax brackets compare to federal brackets?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Connecticut’s top marginal rate is generally lower than the top
                federal rate, but CT brackets start at relatively low income
                levels. Many middle‑income households will see a combined
                marginal rate that includes both federal and CT tax. This
                calculator isolates the <strong>state</strong> portion only.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Where can I find the official Connecticut forms and
                instructions?
              </h3>
              <p>
                For the most accurate and up‑to‑date information, visit the
                <a
                  href="https://portal.ct.gov/drs/individuals/individual-income-tax"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener noreferrer"
                  >Connecticut Department of Revenue Services (DRS)</a
                >. There you can download the CT‑1040, CT‑1040NR/PY, and
                detailed instructions.
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                *This calculator is maintained to reflect the most recent
